text: The site specificities for intercalation of  steffimycin B, adriamycin, echinomycin, and ethidium  bromide  with DNA have been  determined by  CD first-neighbor analysis. The first  three,  which  are antineoplastic  antibiotics, all exhibit preferential binding to sites  comprised of  guanine and  cytosine (GpC, CpG, and  CpC or its complement GpG). Ethidium  bromide displays nonspecific  intercalation.  The results are compared with findings from “ footprinting” studies.  The intercalation of drugs into double-stranded DNA is well  known. Many  intercalating  molecules possess  antibiotic  and/or  antitumor  properties.  For  example,  adriamycin  ( I ) ,   an  anthracyclinone  antibiotic,  is  one  of  several  antineoplastic agents  commercially available for cancer chemotherapy. *  In-  tercalation  raises  the  question  of  specificity of  interaction.  Three  types  of  specificity are commonly associated with the binding of  drugs to DNA:  base  specificity, site specificity, and sequence specificity. Base  specificity  refers to  preferences  shown  by  the  drug  for  a  particular  base  pair  in  DNA.  Site  specificity refers to preferences for particular pairs of  adjacent bases reading in  the 3’-P-5‘ direction along a DNA strand, that is, first neighbor or intercala-  tion sites. Sequence specikity refers to preferences for particular sequences of  bases reading  from  base  to  base  in  the  3’-P-5’ direction on  a  DNA  strand.  Because  a  preferred  sequence  for  binding  may  encompass more  than  two  adjacent  bases, sequence specificity is  not  necessarily a  first-neighbor prop-  erty.

Several  methods  have  been  used  for  examination  of  site  specificities of  intercalation of  drugs into DNA, including fluorescence, resonance Raman, uv,  flow  dichroism, and nmr  spectroscopy2 (for a  recent review, see Ref.  1) and  x-ray  cry~tallography.~-~ One  of  the  most  recent  and  most  powerful  tech-  which involves the nonselec-  niques is the so-called “footprinting”  tive  cleavage of  DNA by  chemical [methidiumpropyl-EDTA- (MPE) Fe(II)]  or enzymatic (DNAase I or DNAase 11) means. DNA fragments that possess  an intercalated  drug are protected from cleavage. MPE,  as an  intercalator,  is  significantly  smaller  than  DNAase,  producing  smaller footprints, which appear more accurate in determining the actual size  and location of  binding sites for small molecules on DNA. CD spectroscopy is  another  very  sensitive  method  for  detecting  the  types  of  conformational  changes  in  DNA  brought  about  by  intercalation  of  a  planar  drug.  CD  first-neighbor  (intercalation  site)  analysis  has  been  previously  used  to  de-  termine site specificities for the binding of  actinomycin D to DNA.12,13 Marck  and  Guschlbauer have voiced  concern  about the mathematical  treatment  of  the  raw  CD data14915 from  these  studies.  In recent  publications,  Allen  and  Gray have satisfactorily resolved  this concernl6,l7 and have reported  relative  preferences  for intercalation  sites and combinations of  intercalation  sites for  actinomycin  D-DNA  binding.17 The  results  of  the  CD  analysis  indicated  that  GpC  and  CpG  are  the  most  favorable  sites  for  intercalation,  in  good  agreement  with  footprinting  res~lts.~.~*'O For  example,  from  DNAase  I  footprinting,  Scamrov  and  Beabealashvilli  determined  that  GpC  and  CpG  were involved as actinomycin D binding sites.g Using the same technique, Fox  and Waring found GpC to be an important  binding site for actinomycin  D."  Results  of  MPE  footprinting  studies  of  actinomycin  D-DNA  binding  by  Van  Dyke et al. indicate that the binding centers around GC base pairs.6

The natural  DNAs  were  used  without  further  purification.  All  synthetic  DNAs were dialyzed three  times for 24  h  each  time against  fresh changes of  100  mL  0.05M phosphate  buffer  (pH = 6.8)  a t   4OC.  Dialysis  tubing  was  prepared  by  boiling the tubing  for 20  min in an aqueous solution  containing  0.1% sodium lauryl sulfate (wt/wt)  and 0.1% EDTA (wt/wt),  and then rinsing  in distilled water.  The tubing was stored under  distilled  water  in a refrigera-  tor. All stock solutions of  DNA were prepared  in the 0.05M  phosphate buffer  (pH = 6.8) t o  have a  concentration of  approximately  one absorbance unit  as  measured by uv spectroscopy a t  260 nm.  UV  and  visible  spectra  were  measured  on  a  Cary  Model  14  recording  spectrophotometer (Varian  Associates, Instrument  Division, Palo  Alto,  CA).  CD  spectra  were  measured  on  a  Jasco  Model  J-40C  automatic  recording  spectropolarimeter (Japanese Spectroscopic Company, Ltd., Tokyo, Japan) set  up for CD only. Storage and manipulation of  CD data, except for steffimycin  B, was accomplished through  the use of  a  PDP 11/04  minicomputer  (Digital  Electronics Corporation, Maynard, MA). Plots of  CD spectra were made by a  Hewlett-Packard  7202A  graphic  plotter  (Hewlett-Packard  Company,  Palo  Alto, CA). The final CD perturbation  curves were drawn by a Bausch & Lomb  DMP-29 plotter  (Bausch & Lomb, Instruments  & Systems Division, Roches-  ter, NY).

The salt displays less in vitro activity  than  does  s t e h y c i n   B  and  no  in  vivo  activity  in  mice  infected  with  gram-positive organisms.lg The sodium  salt  has  an  intense  purple  color,  as  contrasted with the yellow color of  s t e h y c i n  B itself.

For reasons of  solubility, the sodium salt of  steffimycin B was used  in this  study.  In  the  presence  of  the  phosphate  buffer  in  which  the  DNAs  were  dissolved, the salt reverted to the normal steffimycin B, as evidenced by  the  distinct color change from purple to yellow. Titrations of  the phosphate buffer  with  lOP5M NaOH solution (the solvent for the salt of  s t e h y c i n  B) clearly  showed that the buffering capacity of  the phosphate buffer was not exceeded  upon addition of  the sodium hydroxide solution. The stock antibiotic solution  was  prepared  by  dissolving  the  sodium  salt  of  steffimycin  B  in  a  10-5M  solution  of  aqueous  NaOH  to  a  concentration  of  1.52 X  10-5M. As  men-  tioned  previously, the  necessary  amount  of  steffimycin B  was added  to  the  buffer  solution  to  obtain  the  appropriate  concentration  of  free  antibiotic,  which was measured as the baseline. Data were recorded from 320 to 220 nm  at 2.5-nm intervals.

For this reason, a procedure different from that used  for steffimycin B and adriamycin had to be employed. Waring and co-workers  have used a solvent-partition method to study the binding of  echinomycin to  DNA.20.21 Other  workers  have  studied  the  binding  of  water-insoluble  com-  SITE SPECIFICITY OF BINDING OF ANTIBIOTlCS  pounds  to  DNA  by  a  "solid-shake"  method.22 The method  chosen  for  this  study was that of  solid-shake.

The method involves shaking solid echinomycin with a solution of  DNA for  a  given  time,  followed  by  centrifugation  to  remove  any  undissolved  echinomycin. A rotary shaker could not adequately mix the antibiotic and the  DNA solution  because of  echinomycin's tendency  to float on  top of  the DNA  solution. A tumbling stirrer, consisting of  a circular plywood disk rotated by a  variable-speed mechanical stirring motor, was made to overcome this problem.  The  disk  had  provisions  for  securing  eight  1- or  2-mL  tightly  stoppered  volumetric test tubes, in which the DNA solution and solid echinomycin were  placed.  Tumbling a t  a  slow speed ensured minimal shearing of  the DNA  and  maximum  contact of  the DNA with the antibiotic.

Ethidium bromide is a water-soluble quaternary ammonium salt; the proce-  dure employed to examine its binding to DNA was analogous t o  that used for  steffiycin B and adriamycin. CD spectra of  ten DNAs (calf  thymus,  E .  coli,  B.  subtilis,  M .   lysodeikticus, chicken  red  blood  cell,  poly[d(AT)]  . [d(AT)],  POlY[d(GC)I  *  [d(GC)I,  POlY[d(ACT)I  . [d(AGT)I,  POlY[d(AAC)I  . [d(G'M')I,  and  poly[d(AAT)]  *  [d(ATT])  were  measured  in  the  absence  and  increasing  presence  of  ethidium bromide.  The method  of  Allen and Gray"  was employed to analyze the CD spectro-  scopic data of the drug-DNA  complexes. Intercalation  of  the drug to DNA is  accompanied by  a change in the conformation of  the local site, which should  in  turn lead  t o  a  change in  the contribution  of  that site to the overall DNA  CD spectrum.  Figure  1 illustrates  typical  CD  spectra  for  native  DNA  and  DNA in  the  presence  of  increasing  amounts  of  intercalator  (steffimycin B).  The  major  differences in  the  spectra,  i.e.,  the  change  in  magnitude  of  the  JONES, HOLLSTEIN, AND ALLEN

positive  and negative  maxima, are characteristically observed for  each  drug  and  DNA  investigated.  Additionally, in several cases, bathochromic  shifts of  the positive maxima are observed. As  binding levels increase, the CD change  should  increase proportionally.  However, the magnitude of  the CD perturba-  tion  a t  each  site is unknown. Low  levels of  binding  could  conceivably cause  large  perturbations  in  the  DNA  CD  spectrum.  Conversely,  high  levels  of  binding  could  possibly  result  in  only  slight  perturbations.  The  degree  of  perturbation in  the CD spectrum of  the complex is determined by  the extent  of  DNA conformational change upon binding. Thus caution should be used in  interpreting  the  intensities  of  the  CD  changes  as  a  measure  of  binding  strength. This method could miss an intercalation site if  the CD change upon  binding is fortuitously small. However, large perturbations must be considered  good evidence for binding of  the drug to particular  sites in the DNA.  It is  not  unreasonable  to expect  that, upon  binding,  each  drug  will  cause  different  conformational changes a t  intercalation  sites.  Therefore,  the differ-  ing CD perturbations a t  specific binding sites for each drug (e.g., Figs. 2-5)  are  likely to be the result  of  different conformations of  those sites.

When  the first-neighbor method  is applied  to DNA-drug  complexes, ques-  tions  often  arise  about  the  negligibility  of  the  CD  of  the  intercalator  or,  indeed,  the induced  CD  of  the intercalator  in  the  chiral  first-neighbor  unit  environment.  These contributions may  not be negligible and, in  fact, are not  neglected  by  the method.  Both  of  the above CD contributions  will  occur in  proportion t o  the amount of  intercalator binding to a particular first-neighbor  site, and  whatever  the  magnitudes,  they  will  be  partitioned  along  with  the  perturbation  to the first-neighbor CD into a  total  CD perturbation  for  that  first-neighbor  site.  It  is  this  total  CD  perturbation  that  is  diagnostic  for  binding  at the first-neighbor unit  in  question.  To put  the above in  different  terms, it is clear that one could follow, say by equilibrium dialysis, the CD of  the ligand,  whether  it  be  ordinary,  induced  or  both  as the  ligand  binds  to  DNA.  By making such measurements as a function of  varying first neighbors  one could  begin  to understand  which first neighbors offer attractive binding  sites for the ligand. Another  approach  would  be to observe perturbations in  the CD of  the DNA first-neighbor units  as the ligand binds. This too would  bring  about  understanding  as to  which  first  neighbors  bind  the  ligands.  Actually,  since CD changes occur in the ligands as well as the first-neighbor  units  simultaneously,  the  above  two  experiments  cannot  be  separated.  The  CD perturbation  partitioning technique extracts the binding information from  all  types  of  CD  changes  and  presents  it in  terms  of  first-neighbor  binding  specificity.

One  of  the  assumptions upon  which  the matrix  method  rests  is  that  the  geometry and electronic coupling between stacked bases and hence the CD of  first-neighbor units is unchanged unless binding  occurs a t  that first neighbor  unit.  It is clear that an agent that bound a t  point  A  but caused  a structural  change at point  B would violate this assumption.  An  example of  this type of  phenomenon might occur in the first-neighbor units between those involved in  the binding of  the two ligand moieties in echinomycin. If  the intervening first  neighbor  is  random,  the  error  is  unimportant  since  it  will  appear  in  all  first-neighbor units  as a  small perturbation.  If  the first-neighbor  unit  is not  random, then a significant CD perturbation not correlated with direct binding  SITE SPECIFICITY OF BINDING OF ANTIBIOTICS  could appear. This possibility is described in detail in  the subsequent section  specific to echinomycin.  Steffimycin B (2) was first isolated in  1974 from Streptomyces elgreteus by  Brodasky  and Reusser.lg It was  subsequently  shown to possess antileukemic  activity  in  cell  cultures  and  to inhibit  gram-positive  bacteria.lg  From  RNA  polymerase  and  DNA  polymerase  I  inhibition  studies  employing  synthetic  DNAs  as  templates,  Reusser  has  stated  that  steffimycin  B  interacts,  via  intercalation,  primarily  with adenine and/or  thymine bases in  DNA.24 Like-  wise,  from  fluorescence studies,  Dall’acqua  et  al.  have  suggested  that  ApT  (3’-5’)  constitutes a good site for intercalation of  this a n t i b i ~ t i c . ~ ~

Complexation  of  steffimycin  B with  DNA  produces  significant  changes  in  the CD spectrum of  the complex relative to that of  the native DNA  (Fig. 1).  As discussed previously, these changes are the result of  altered  conformations  of  the  DNA  binding  sites  brought  about  by  intercalation  of  the  drug.  Al-  though  both example DNAs exhibit perturbed  CD spectra, the magnitude  of  perturbation is greater for the poly[d(GC)]  . [d(GC)] than for the poly[d(AT)]  . [d(AT)]. This is suggestive of  greater conformational changes for the former  polymer upon binding of  steffimycin B.

Plots  of  the CD perturbation  upon  binding  of  steffimycin B  to DNA  for  various  combinations  of  first-neighbor  units  as  described  in  Ref.  17  are  presented  in  Fig.  2.  The  first-neighbor  units  CpG  and  CpC  are  markedly  perturbed,  CpG  to  a  greater  extent.  Comparison  of  CpG + GpC  with  CpG  reveals a mirror image relationship.  The contribution to CpG + GpC by GpC  must be  so  great  that it overcomes the contribution  by  CpG  and  causes an  opposite  perturbation.  Very  little  perturbation,  probably  consistent  with  negligible  binding,  is  observed  for  the  first-neighbor  units  ApA  or  APT.  Combinations of  nearest-neighbor units that include positive contributions by  CpG (ApC - APT + CpG and TpC + ApT + CpG) are similar in appearance  t o   CpG.  The  decreased  magnitude  of  perturbation  of  the  former  two  is  suggestive of  a t  least some intercalation  with  ApC and TpC (since ApT was  previously  demonstrated  to  be  a  poor  site,  it  can  be  neglected).  Likewise,  combinations  of  first-neighbor  units  that  include  negative  contributions  by  CpG  (ApG - APT  - CpG  and  TpG + APT - CpG)  are  dominated  by  the  negative curve constructed from CpG. As above, the diminished perturbation  is  probably  attributable  to binding  of  steffiycin B by  ApC  and  TpG.  The  results  of  this study indicate strong preferential  binding  of  steffimycin  B  to  intercalation sites that contain both cytosine and guanine, specifically GpC >  CpG > CpC. The  curves  that  correspond  to  combinations  with  positive  contributions by CpG are quite different from each other. ApC - ApT + CpG  resembles  CpG, but exhibits  greater  perturbation.  Considering the relatively  minor  contribution  of  APT,  interpretation  of  ApC  - APT + CpG  suggests  that ApC  is  less perturbed  than CpG, but more  perturbed  than  APT,  ApA,  and TpA. Unlike the analogous case for steffimycin B, TpC 1 ApT + CpG for  adriamycin does not resemble ApC  - APT + CpG. TpC is a t  least comparable  in  terms  of  site  preference  to  ApC.  The  final  two  combinations  possess  negative  contributions  by  CpG.  Interestingly,  ApC  - ApT + CpG  and  ApG  - APT - CpG  are almost  exact  mirror  images of  each  other.  The  dif-  ferences arise from the difference in  the sign of  the CpG contribution  to the  combination  and  the  presence  of  ApG  in  ApG - ApT  - CpG  and  ApC  in  ApC  - ApT + CpG.  This  mirror  relationship  is  suggestive  of  opposite  CD  perturbations  for ApG and ApC by  adriamycin. TpG + ApT  - CpG exhibits  opposite perturbation to that expected for the inverse of  CpG; the binding to  TpG appears the same magnitude as that for ApG. Figure 4  displays the CD perturbations for ‘echinomycin binding to various  synthetic and natural DNAs. Large perturbations are apparent for CpC, CpG,  and CpG + GpC.  From  the previous results  of  Van  Dyke  and  DervanY7 the  large change in the CD contribution of  the CpG upit is not surprising. CpG is  not implicated in their data as a direct binding site; nonetheless, each time it  occurs in  one of  the four  base  sequences proposed to bind  echinomycin, the  geometry  and electronic coupling of  the CpG unit  are altered  strongly upon  binding.  Not all CpG units show this perturbation; only those CpG units that  occur  in  appropriate  sequences are  altered.  To  a  first  approximation,  the  number of  such altered CpG units is proportional to the total number of  CpG  units in  the double-stranded structure.  This  proportionality  causes the  CD  changes, which are actually due to a fraction of  the CpG units to be ascribed  t o  them all. The consequence is that the CpG CD contribution will be altered  by  the  binding  of  echinomycin whether  it  binds  the  drug  directly  or  not  because  of  the intimate association of  the CpG unit (and only the CpG unit)  with the binding sites. This perturbation may be viewed as a confirmation of  the Van Dyke and Dervan results. Comparison of the plots for CpG alone and  the combination of  CpG with GpC indicates that GpC is a heavily perturbed  intercalation  site. ApA and ApT exhibit little perturbation.  The combination  of  TpA  and  ApT  is  the  negative  of  APT  alone,  which  argues  that  the  perturbation  from  TpA is more substantial than that  from APT. Wavelength in nm  None  of  the  antibiotics  investigated  exhibit  random  intercalation  into  double-stranded  DNA,  although  adriamycin  seems  to  display  the  least  specificity. Interestingly, all the antibiotics tested (and from an earlier investi-  gation, actinomycin D17) demonstrate a marked propensity for intercalation  into sites that possess both guanine and cytosine, despite the fact that only  steffiycin B and adriamycin are structurally related. Ethidium bromide, as  expected, showed no clear preference for binding sites.  From these curves it is apparent that all the sites, or combinations of  the sites,  are perturbed by binding. Also, a pyrimidine (3’-5’)  purine preference over a  purine  (3’-5’)  pyrimidine site  is  not  evident.  Clearly, the  binding must  be  characterized  as nonspecific, and  this  result  confirms the  experiments done  with  ethidium  binding  and  with methidium  footprinting by  earlier workers.  Thus, it is possible to correlate the results of  our binding analysis by CD with  other methods.  The CD method  for determination of  site specificity of  drug intercalation  into DNA  is fairly straightforward and  no  more difficult than  footprinting.  The results reported  above suggest that this technique may  be  employed in  complementary fashion to independently  confirm  or  at least  to compare to  footprinting results.  (1980)  Proc.  Natl.
